WEBVTT

00:00.567 --> 00:01.935
Narrator:
Tonight on "Shark Tank"...

00:01.935 --> 00:02.703
Sharks!         Sharks!

00:03.570 --> 00:03.604
Sharks!         Sharks!

00:03.604 --> 00:04.738
What is up?!

00:04.738 --> 00:06.373
Who's ready
to take the plunge?

00:06.373 --> 00:07.307
[ Screams ]

00:07.307 --> 00:08.375
Don't be a wimp.

00:08.375 --> 00:09.643
You better be selling
a lot of them.

00:09.643 --> 00:10.878
$4.9 million in sales.

00:10.878 --> 00:11.912
-Wow.
-Wow.

00:11.912 --> 00:13.747
I'll give you
$5 million.

00:13.747 --> 00:15.315
-Whoa!
-Whoa!

00:15.315 --> 00:16.416
It's a loan-shark deal.

00:16.416 --> 00:18.452
You're the walking,
talking billboard

00:18.452 --> 00:19.786
of how to do it right.

00:19.786 --> 00:20.988
But wait,
there's more.

00:20.988 --> 00:23.023
-Oh, there's more.
-Boom!

00:23.023 --> 00:31.431
♪♪

00:31.431 --> 00:33.867
Narrator: First in the Tank
is a convenient version

00:33.867 --> 00:35.602
of a popular cuisine.

00:35.602 --> 00:40.741
♪♪

00:40.741 --> 00:45.846
♪♪

00:45.846 --> 00:47.681
Sharks!          Sharks!

00:47.681 --> 00:49.783
We are pumped
to be here.

00:49.783 --> 00:52.819
My name is Dok.
My name's Junghun.

00:52.819 --> 00:54.688
And we're from...

00:57.391 --> 00:58.792
[ Laughter ]

00:58.792 --> 01:01.161
...Cupbop!        ...Cupbop!

01:01.161 --> 01:03.697
Junghun,
what is Cupbop?

01:03.697 --> 01:05.265
Cupbop?

01:05.265 --> 01:06.233
C...

01:06.233 --> 01:07.968
[ Laughter ]
...U...

01:07.968 --> 01:09.102
...P...

01:09.102 --> 01:12.339
...B...O...P!

01:12.339 --> 01:14.708
Cupbop!
Cupbop! Cupbop!

01:14.708 --> 01:18.812
Cupbop is Korean barbecue
in a cup.

01:18.812 --> 01:22.816
We are super energetic...

01:22.816 --> 01:25.986
little bit crazy...

01:25.986 --> 01:29.089
quick-service
Korean barbecue brand.

01:29.089 --> 01:32.993
Did you know that there's
only one Asian concept

01:32.993 --> 01:36.196
in the top 50
quick-service restaurants?

01:36.196 --> 01:37.798
Hm.
There's room for more,

01:37.798 --> 01:39.333
and we are next!

01:39.333 --> 01:43.637
K-pop, K-drama,
K-movies taking over.

01:43.637 --> 01:45.305
It's time for...

01:45.305 --> 01:47.007
K-food!         K-food!

01:47.007 --> 01:49.309
To take over the world!

01:49.309 --> 01:52.079
We have an offer for...

01:52.079 --> 01:56.550
3% for our company
for $1 million.

01:56.550 --> 01:57.484
-What?!
-Hello!

01:57.484 --> 01:59.786
Wow!
That's a lot of barbecue.

01:59.786 --> 02:01.221
-What?!
-Wow.

02:01.221 --> 02:04.825
Sharks, we'll keep
making the Cupbops,

02:04.825 --> 02:06.860
you keep swimming
in cash.

02:06.860 --> 02:08.495
Swim, swim.

02:08.495 --> 02:10.831
[ Laughter ]
Swim.

02:10.831 --> 02:12.499
Hey, Sharks!

02:12.499 --> 02:15.369
We have a Cupbop
for each of you guys.

02:15.369 --> 02:16.837
Now...

02:16.837 --> 02:18.839
Shh!       Shh!

02:18.839 --> 02:20.307
Just eat!     Just eat!

02:20.307 --> 02:22.142
O'Leary: Oh, fantastic.
Wow.

02:22.142 --> 02:23.410
Greiner: Oh, my God.

02:23.410 --> 02:24.778
What a presentation.

02:24.778 --> 02:26.013
All right. What's in here?
Fantastic.

02:26.013 --> 02:27.614
Tell us what's in it
before we go in.

02:27.614 --> 02:28.682
Oh, spicy.

02:28.682 --> 02:30.417
It's 100%
sweet potato noodle

02:30.417 --> 02:32.919
on the side,
a cold chop chip.

02:32.919 --> 02:36.056
And we have a bulgogi.
It's beef.

02:36.056 --> 02:38.992
And hot spicy pork
on the side.

02:38.992 --> 02:40.594
It's hot.
Greiner: So beef and pork mixed?

02:40.594 --> 02:42.329
-It's hot.
-Yeah, it's hot.

02:42.329 --> 02:43.497
Whoa.

02:43.497 --> 02:45.399
It's hot.
It is great!

02:45.399 --> 02:46.933
[ Laughs ] Thank you.

02:46.933 --> 02:48.335
-And, Barbara?
-It's yummy.

02:48.335 --> 02:49.870
Kwon: It's not a ketchup.
It's a spicy food.

02:49.870 --> 02:50.937
-That's right.
-Yummy.

02:50.937 --> 02:52.205
Are you okay, Mark?
Are you crying?

02:52.205 --> 02:53.407
You all right?
No, I'm good.

02:53.407 --> 02:56.610
So we have a spice level
from 1 to 10,

02:56.610 --> 02:58.045
and our customers
can choose that.

02:58.045 --> 02:59.780
O'Leary: We've had
a lot of different food concepts

02:59.780 --> 03:01.515
on "Shark Tank."
I have to give it to you.

03:01.515 --> 03:03.684
This is one of the best
I've ever tried.

03:03.684 --> 03:05.519
Whoa! Thank you!
Yeah!

03:05.519 --> 03:07.120
That's big
coming from Kevin.

03:07.120 --> 03:08.755
Guys, what's
the cost of this?

03:08.755 --> 03:12.793
Kwon: It ranges anywhere
from about $8 to $10 per bowl.

03:12.793 --> 03:14.795
Greiner: And what
does it cost you?

03:14.795 --> 03:16.296
$1.80 to $2.50.

03:16.296 --> 03:18.765
So our gross margin
is about 75%.

03:18.765 --> 03:21.068
And you gave us
an astronomical number here.

03:21.068 --> 03:23.904
You said 3%.
You wanted a million dollars.

03:23.904 --> 03:26.106
Yeah.
Your sales must be
through the roof.

03:26.106 --> 03:27.507
Let's hear it.

03:27.507 --> 03:31.278
Our trailing 12 months,
system-wide sales

03:31.278 --> 03:33.080
is $18.7 million.

03:33.080 --> 03:34.147
-Oh, there you go.
-Whoa!

03:34.147 --> 03:35.549
-Whoa!
-Wow.

03:35.549 --> 03:37.017
Wow!

03:37.017 --> 03:39.019
Are you kidding?
How many trucks?

03:39.019 --> 03:42.189
So we actually -- We started
from a food truck.

03:42.189 --> 03:45.792
Now the trucks are more
of a marketing tool for us.

03:45.792 --> 03:49.930
Brick and mortar stores,
we right now have 27 stores.

03:49.930 --> 03:51.998
How many years have you
been in business?

03:51.998 --> 03:53.667
About eight years.

03:53.667 --> 03:56.503
Herjavec: Congratulations.
Tell us the sales trajectory.

03:56.503 --> 03:58.805
I want to know
how you got to $18 million.

03:58.805 --> 04:03.610
Going back the last kind of
5 years, we were $7 million,

04:03.610 --> 04:05.245
$8 million, $9 million.

04:05.245 --> 04:07.314
So we were growing
about a million each.

04:07.314 --> 04:12.185
And last year, we did
right around $10.5 million.

04:12.185 --> 04:15.288
And this year, we're expected
to grow 90% this year.

04:15.288 --> 04:17.758
And during a COVID year,
when people were not

04:17.758 --> 04:19.059
going out to restaurants.

04:19.059 --> 04:20.560
So how did you do that?
Yeah.

04:20.560 --> 04:24.598
So we shut our dining down
like everybody else.

04:24.598 --> 04:26.533
Did only takeout.

04:26.533 --> 04:28.268
And delivery.
And delivery.

04:28.268 --> 04:31.238
And our same store sales,
we were up 9% during COVID.

04:31.238 --> 04:32.572
Wow.
So that worked better

04:32.572 --> 04:33.974
for you, actually?
Yeah.

04:33.974 --> 04:35.942
Herjavec: Dok,
what's your background?

04:35.942 --> 04:38.912
Yeah, so previous to this,
I was an investor

04:38.912 --> 04:40.647
at a major hedge fund.

04:40.647 --> 04:43.283
Actually, he was
my first customer.

04:43.283 --> 04:46.887
When I owned the food truck in
Salt Lake City, downtown.

04:46.887 --> 04:48.021
Wow.
He came to me,

04:48.021 --> 04:49.689
"Hey, we love Korean!

04:49.689 --> 04:51.224
Hey, we love Korean!"
Yeah.

04:51.224 --> 04:54.194
So I'm Korean, and just
fell in love with the product.

04:54.194 --> 04:55.862
I went,
moved to New York,

04:55.862 --> 04:58.799
did my kind of seven,
eight years there,

04:58.799 --> 05:01.268
and I just wanted
something different.

05:01.268 --> 05:04.037
Did you go and pitch him
on being his partner?

05:04.037 --> 05:05.071
He called me.
That's right.

05:05.071 --> 05:06.239
I called him up.

05:06.239 --> 05:08.809
But he said, "If you not
hire me right now,

05:08.809 --> 05:10.911
you're gonna regret it
for the future."

05:10.911 --> 05:12.879
Who owns the business,
and what percentage?

05:12.879 --> 05:16.082
So we own half
of the business.

05:16.082 --> 05:18.318
Oh, so you've raised
a lot of money then?

05:18.318 --> 05:20.554
No, we've actually

05:20.554 --> 05:22.122
never raised money.
With all that growth?

05:22.122 --> 05:23.590
Who owns the other half?
Who owns the other half?

05:23.590 --> 05:26.293
The other half,
his co-founders.

05:26.293 --> 05:28.461
Oh, okay.
And a group came in

05:28.461 --> 05:31.698
and just bought equity
off of the other three partners.

05:31.698 --> 05:33.099
What did they pay
for that equity?

05:33.099 --> 05:34.201
What valuation?

05:34.201 --> 05:35.902
Undisclosed.
We don't know.

05:35.902 --> 05:37.337
You don't know?
They haven't told us.
Yeah.

05:37.337 --> 05:39.573
So your ex-partners
are just gone basically.

05:39.573 --> 05:40.774
They took the money and ran.
Yes.

05:40.774 --> 05:42.709
So we've actually --
So we've been growing

05:42.709 --> 05:43.977
through organic cash flow.

05:43.977 --> 05:45.178
We've never raised money,
actually.

05:45.178 --> 05:46.713
Good for you.
But during COVID,

05:46.713 --> 05:47.914
you pivoted, right?
Yeah.

05:47.914 --> 05:50.417
Instead of having people
go to the stores,

05:50.417 --> 05:52.752
you said you were doing
delivery business.
Mm-hmm.

05:52.752 --> 05:55.488
You killed it last year.
Why do you need a store?

05:55.488 --> 05:58.592
The reason why --
it's not only about the food.

05:58.592 --> 06:00.427
We want to give you
a really good experience

06:00.427 --> 06:01.962
with our customer.

06:01.962 --> 06:04.130
We high-five
all the time.

06:04.130 --> 06:06.533
We're hugging.
We're dancing together.

06:06.533 --> 06:10.237
Korean people is a party people.
They're having fun.

06:10.237 --> 06:11.638
They know how to play.

06:11.638 --> 06:12.973
Cuban: You said
you hadn't raised any money.

06:12.973 --> 06:14.407
Yeah.
Why didn't you bring in

06:14.407 --> 06:16.109
any investors
before you got here?

06:16.109 --> 06:19.012
We got so many investors
came to us.

06:19.012 --> 06:22.249
But I say no
for eight years,

06:22.249 --> 06:28.321
because I think I can make
2,000 stores with you guys.

06:28.321 --> 06:31.124
I want to be
the first Korean national brand

06:31.124 --> 06:32.792
with the Sharks.

06:32.792 --> 06:35.662
When I came here
a long time ago from Korea,

06:35.662 --> 06:38.632
I'm not good student
in Korea.

06:38.632 --> 06:41.568
I got F-grades
all my life.

06:41.568 --> 06:44.537
They call me, I'm the failure.
I'm the loser.

06:44.537 --> 06:46.072
But when I came
to the United States,

06:46.072 --> 06:48.608
I found opportunity here.

06:48.608 --> 06:52.913
If I work hard here,
I can make a dream come here.

06:52.913 --> 06:56.683
This is a big thing for me,
not because of money.

06:56.683 --> 06:59.319
I want to get the opportunity
to tell them,

06:59.319 --> 07:02.022
"Hey, first Korean
national brand here."

07:02.022 --> 07:03.723
So, Junghun, we heard
all about you.

07:03.723 --> 07:05.225
Fabulous story.
I love it.

07:05.225 --> 07:07.594
But, Dok, I want to hear
a little bit about you.

07:07.594 --> 07:09.462
Kwon: Yeah.
I was born in Korea.

07:09.462 --> 07:14.834
And when I was 11, my family
came on a summer vacation

07:14.834 --> 07:18.738
in the U. S., and the day before
we were supposed to fly back,

07:18.738 --> 07:22.642
my mom and dad sat me down
and my older brother and said,

07:22.642 --> 07:25.011
"Oh, by the way,
we didn't tell you,

07:25.011 --> 07:26.913
but you guys are not
coming back with us."

07:26.913 --> 07:28.348
Oh!
What?

07:28.348 --> 07:31.017
Corcoran: Wow.
So they had planned
this all along.

07:31.017 --> 07:34.421
So they found a family,
a school,

07:34.421 --> 07:37.023
and they thought
that if they told us,

07:37.023 --> 07:38.925
we wouldn't want to come,

07:38.925 --> 07:40.627
and so they
did it the hard way.

07:40.627 --> 07:42.495
The next day, bam.

07:42.495 --> 07:43.863
My God.
Wow.

07:43.863 --> 07:48.201
And they chose Utah
because they just heard

07:48.201 --> 07:50.203
that Utah was
a religious state,

07:50.203 --> 07:52.305
that a lot of people
don't smoke and drink.

07:52.305 --> 07:54.007
They thought, "Oh, that's
got to be safe."

07:54.007 --> 07:56.309
[ Laughter ]
"We're sending them to Utah."

07:56.309 --> 08:00.146
Dok, I mean,
that story is incredible.

08:00.146 --> 08:02.515
Why do you think
your parents did that?

08:02.515 --> 08:05.552
Why did they drop you off
in America?

08:05.552 --> 08:08.188
It was really
for the opportunity.

08:08.188 --> 08:11.825
Absolute best decision
that they've ever made for us.

08:11.825 --> 08:14.694
And I am just
forever grateful

08:14.694 --> 08:16.062
for what they've
been, you know --

08:16.062 --> 08:17.530
It's amazing how
the people who grew up here

08:17.530 --> 08:19.165
don't feel the same way.

08:19.165 --> 08:22.235
Think about what
your parents sacrificed

08:22.235 --> 08:23.903
for the American dream.
Yeah.

08:23.903 --> 08:27.674
I now only can I really
start understanding my parents

08:27.674 --> 08:29.809
a little bit now
that I have my own kids

08:29.809 --> 08:31.277
and the love
that I have for them.

08:31.277 --> 08:34.347
He got two kids.
I got five kids.

08:34.347 --> 08:35.448
-Wow!
-Oh!

08:35.448 --> 08:36.516
How do you work?

08:36.516 --> 08:37.517
Maybe that's why
you work so hard.

08:37.517 --> 08:40.420
But my wife
supports me 100%.

08:40.420 --> 08:41.988
I love this story.

08:41.988 --> 08:46.693
Like you guys, my dad gave up
everything to come here.

08:46.693 --> 08:51.765
I had to freakin' be successful
to justify that sacrifice.

08:51.765 --> 08:53.333
Yeah.
And you guys are

08:53.333 --> 08:54.768
on to something here.

08:54.768 --> 08:57.170
Purpose comes through
everything

08:57.170 --> 09:00.740
except $1 million for 3%.

09:00.740 --> 09:02.042
[ Laughs ]

09:02.042 --> 09:03.977
I don't know what
the purpose of that is.

09:03.977 --> 09:05.879
What is it,
a $30 million valuation?

09:05.879 --> 09:07.280
Yep. $33 million.

09:07.280 --> 09:10.016
How do I -- How do I --
How do I get there?

09:10.016 --> 09:12.585
Yeah, it's really
the growth rate.

09:12.585 --> 09:16.423
It took us seven years
to get to $10 million.

09:16.423 --> 09:19.059
We have 10 more stores coming
before the end of the year.

09:19.059 --> 09:20.260
O'Leary: I like the deal.

09:20.260 --> 09:22.328
I like the mission.
I like the energy.

09:22.328 --> 09:27.367
I love the food, and I like
the cash <i>flow</i> a lot, okay?

09:27.367 --> 09:28.735
I'm gonna
make you an offer.

09:28.735 --> 09:36.376
♪♪

09:41.581 --> 09:43.349
Narrator:
All Sharks are still in,

09:43.349 --> 09:45.819
and Kevin has an offer
to make for Junghun and Dok's

09:45.819 --> 09:49.522
quick-serve Korean
barbecue business, Cupbop.

09:49.522 --> 09:50.723
O'Leary:
So here's the deal.

09:50.723 --> 09:52.325
I'm gonna loan you
the million dollars,

09:52.325 --> 09:53.827
and I'm gonna put
a 10% interest rate on it.

09:53.827 --> 09:57.030
It's 36 months amortization,
3 years.

09:57.030 --> 09:59.899
And I'm going to take
the 3% as a warrant.

09:59.899 --> 10:01.801
So I get equity.
I get 3%.

10:01.801 --> 10:04.604
I put all I can bring to it
as Chef Wonderful

10:04.604 --> 10:05.872
and all the rest
of that stuff.

10:05.872 --> 10:07.240
And you have
a Shark Tank deal.

10:07.240 --> 10:08.908
Guys, can I get your
attention a moment?

10:08.908 --> 10:10.677
I'm very familiar with
this space because I have

10:10.677 --> 10:13.346
a hugely successful business,
Cousins Maine Lobster,

10:13.346 --> 10:15.582
and they have over
$200 million in sales.

10:15.582 --> 10:17.650
But I also have to
tell you the idea

10:17.650 --> 10:19.586
that you were dumb
in school like I was,

10:19.586 --> 10:23.156
it's interesting to me,
after 13 years on "Shark Tank",

10:23.156 --> 10:27.494
every one of my top-10
business owners/founders

10:27.494 --> 10:29.162
were terrible in school.

10:29.162 --> 10:30.763
Isn't that interesting?

10:30.763 --> 10:31.931
It's interesting.
That is a great point.

10:31.931 --> 10:33.633
And yet, when they
get into the workplace,

10:33.633 --> 10:36.002
boy, oh boy,
are they smart.

10:36.002 --> 10:37.904
So I believe in you,

10:37.904 --> 10:39.506
but it's too rich.

10:39.506 --> 10:41.875
I have to have 30%
for $1 million.

10:41.875 --> 10:42.942
[ Chuckles ]

10:42.942 --> 10:45.044
All right, laugh at it
if you want, okay?

10:45.044 --> 10:49.782
But my sharp thinking on
how I remodel all my businesses

10:49.782 --> 10:52.685
have made them much more money
than that all along the way.

10:52.685 --> 10:54.721
You have two offers.
Are there any other offers?

10:54.721 --> 10:56.923
Herjavec:
The product is fantastic.

10:56.923 --> 11:02.028
I think the business is worth
about $18 million today.

11:02.028 --> 11:03.997
You're asking
for $33 million.

11:03.997 --> 11:05.532
I want to own a bigger piece,

11:05.532 --> 11:07.967
but that's just simply
a function of money.

11:07.967 --> 11:12.138
You're asking for
a million for 3%.

11:12.138 --> 11:15.441
I'll give you $5 million
for 28%.

11:15.441 --> 11:16.943
Oh!
Greiner: Wow.

11:16.943 --> 11:19.846
Which is an $18 million
valuation.
Wow.

11:19.846 --> 11:21.848
I mean, that's what I think
the business is worth today.

11:21.848 --> 11:25.451
Listen, I love your model,
and I just want

11:25.451 --> 11:26.653
to take
the journey with you.

11:26.653 --> 11:29.622
I would give you
a million dollars as a loan.

11:29.622 --> 11:32.625
As a loan.
8% interest, 5% equity.

11:32.625 --> 11:35.261
Hey, guys, if it's just the cash
you're looking for,

11:35.261 --> 11:38.131
I would give you
a million dollar loan for 5%.

11:38.131 --> 11:40.200
No problem.
I'll do it for 3%,

11:40.200 --> 11:41.534
and I'll work on
the finances.
I would do it for 5%.

11:41.534 --> 11:43.203
And you know what?
I do it with Barbara

11:43.203 --> 11:44.370
if Barbara wants
to do it with me.

11:44.370 --> 11:45.638
I would love to do it.

11:45.638 --> 11:47.073
I haven't done a deal with you
in a dog's age.

11:47.073 --> 11:48.341
That's right.
We haven't.

11:48.341 --> 11:49.943
So Lori and I
will give you 5%

11:49.943 --> 11:52.045
for a million dollar loan,
we'll go in together.

11:52.045 --> 11:53.313
Okay, so...

11:53.313 --> 11:54.614
[ Whispering
indistinctly ]

11:56.449 --> 11:58.318
Mark,
what are you doing?

11:58.318 --> 12:00.386
Cuban: First, I love the
business. I love the product.

12:00.386 --> 12:02.855
I love the fact that you can
make it a healthy alternative.

12:02.855 --> 12:04.791
But what I'm hearing,
and tell me if I'm wrong,

