16:40.566 --> 16:42.268
Narrator: Next in the Tank
is a company

16:42.268 --> 16:46.005
that brings a cool addition
to your wellness routine.

16:46.005 --> 16:51.477
♪♪

16:51.477 --> 16:53.746
Hey, Sharks.
I'm Michael Garrett.

16:53.746 --> 16:55.381
And I'm Ryan Duey.

16:55.381 --> 16:58.217
And we're from
Sacramento, California.

16:58.217 --> 17:00.786
Our company is Plunge,
and we're seeking

17:00.786 --> 17:04.423
$1.2 million for a 5% stake
in our company.

17:04.423 --> 17:05.892
[ Chuckles ]

17:05.892 --> 17:10.429
Sharks, what if I told you
you could lower inflammation,

17:10.429 --> 17:14.300
increase fat loss,
strengthen your immune system,

17:14.300 --> 17:17.770
sleep better,
reduce muscle soreness,

17:17.770 --> 17:21.541
have more energy
in just one minute?

17:21.541 --> 17:24.243
Well, this isn't fiction.
This is reality.

17:24.243 --> 17:28.748
And this is not a bathtub.
This is a cold plunge.

17:28.748 --> 17:30.449
Studies show that
cold plunging

17:30.449 --> 17:32.852
increases
norepinephrine levels

17:32.852 --> 17:34.987
two to three times
their normal amount.

17:36.822 --> 17:38.357
I don't know
what that is, either.

17:38.357 --> 17:39.825
[ Laughter ]
But apparently

17:39.825 --> 17:42.128
that's what leads to all
those incredible benefits.

17:42.128 --> 17:46.032
Sharks, all over the world,
cold exposure is exploding,

17:46.032 --> 17:49.669
but buying 40 pounds of ice
is a huge hassle.

17:49.669 --> 17:52.238
Our revolutionary
cold plunge uses powerful

17:52.238 --> 17:55.007
cooling and filtration
to give you cold,

17:55.007 --> 17:57.877
crystal clear water
whenever you want.

17:57.877 --> 18:00.713
All in a beautiful,
sleek tub.

18:00.713 --> 18:03.149
Just set your temperature
anywhere from 60

18:03.149 --> 18:04.750
all the way down to 39.

18:04.750 --> 18:05.985
Wow.
Oh, wow.

18:05.985 --> 18:08.354
So, Sharks, who's ready
to take the plunge?

18:08.354 --> 18:10.022
Wow.
How about you, Robert?

18:10.022 --> 18:11.691
You look like
you could use a plunge.

18:11.691 --> 18:13.292
I'll try it.
I'll try it.

18:13.292 --> 18:15.261
Let's do it, baby.
Amazing.

18:16.228 --> 18:17.430
What's the temperature
set at?

18:17.430 --> 18:19.198
55 right now.
55? That's not bad.

18:19.198 --> 18:20.700
It's pretty cold.
55 is cold.

18:20.700 --> 18:22.635
No, I've done cold plunges,
like, many times

18:22.635 --> 18:24.403
'cause we have one
at the Mavericks, obviously.

18:24.403 --> 18:27.106
Why can't I fill up my tub
with cold enough water?

18:27.106 --> 18:29.108
Cold out of the tap
isn't gonna be,

18:29.108 --> 18:31.477
you know, 55,
maybe some times of the year,

18:31.477 --> 18:32.845
if you're in
a cold environment.

18:32.845 --> 18:34.947
You can throw ice in it, though?
Can you throw ice --

18:34.947 --> 18:36.482
That's what most people
do right now.

18:36.482 --> 18:38.250
You do throw ice?
They're buying ice,
and then it's like

18:38.250 --> 18:39.919
they have to drain it
right after.

18:39.919 --> 18:41.654
Where our unit,
it's always filtering.

18:41.654 --> 18:43.389
It's always set.
It's always clean.

18:43.389 --> 18:45.391
It's about --
Oh, lord.

18:45.391 --> 18:48.027
[ Laughter ]

18:48.027 --> 18:49.295
All right!
All right.

18:49.295 --> 18:51.364
The key here is gonna be
anchoring to your breath.

18:51.364 --> 18:52.999
Your body is gonna want
to be really excited

18:52.999 --> 18:54.500
and you're gonna want
to get out,

18:54.500 --> 18:56.102
but you want to override
that with slow, long breaths.

18:56.102 --> 18:57.503
Just relax, Robert.

18:57.503 --> 19:01.140
How long is he supposed to hold
back the urge to jump out?

19:01.140 --> 19:02.475
Two minutes.
Greiner: Here he goes!

19:02.475 --> 19:03.442
Two minutes
is ideal.

19:03.442 --> 19:04.910
-Oh!
-Oh, geez!

19:04.910 --> 19:06.312
Cuban: You can't
do that, Robert.

19:06.312 --> 19:08.280
You just got to get in.
Don't be a wimp.

19:08.280 --> 19:10.116
So do I just --
Yeah.

19:10.116 --> 19:11.317
Just lay back,
get comfortable.

19:11.317 --> 19:14.020
-Robert! Robert!
-Focus in on the breath.

19:14.020 --> 19:17.223
[ Sharks chanting,
"Robert! Robert!" ]

19:17.223 --> 19:18.858
[ Screams ]

19:18.858 --> 19:21.193
[ Laughter ]
Slow breaths, Robert.

19:22.028 --> 19:23.796
[ Screams ]
Slow breaths.

19:23.796 --> 19:25.731
-In the nose.
-Come on, here we go.

19:25.731 --> 19:28.701
Is that a minute?!
Garrett: You got this.
Override the body.

19:28.701 --> 19:30.803
Your mind wants to get out.
Just breathe through it.

19:30.803 --> 19:32.338
It's just your body's
loving this.

19:32.338 --> 19:34.340
You're totally safe.
Shut up!

19:34.340 --> 19:36.108
[ Laughter ]

19:36.108 --> 19:39.345
Slow down the breathing.
Nice, slow breaths. Beautiful.

19:39.345 --> 19:40.613
Be one with the cold.

19:40.613 --> 19:42.081
He's gonna feel
incredible after.

19:42.081 --> 19:43.416
I'm feeling really cold.

19:43.416 --> 19:45.351
Are you feeling like numb,
like you're getting used to it?

19:45.351 --> 19:46.986
Like, it's not as bad
as when you first got in?

19:46.986 --> 19:48.354
It's shocking.

19:48.354 --> 19:51.424
But surprisingly,
the breathing really helps.

19:51.424 --> 19:53.059
And now it doesn't feel
as bad.

19:53.059 --> 19:56.195
I wouldn't say it's comfortable,
but it's not bad.

19:56.195 --> 19:57.530
I'm getting out.

19:57.530 --> 19:58.964
Grab him a towel
right there.

19:58.964 --> 20:00.866
Oh, my God.

20:00.866 --> 20:02.168
Wow.

20:02.168 --> 20:04.170
Mark, why do they do it?
Why do the athletes do it?

20:04.170 --> 20:06.739
It helps with inflammation.
I'll just put my leg in.

20:06.739 --> 20:08.708
Actually, it's incredible.

20:08.708 --> 20:10.543
Like you feel
your blood flowing.

20:10.543 --> 20:12.078
Like, seriously,
Like I feel --

20:12.078 --> 20:13.546
No, it wakes you up. If you go
all in, it wakes you up.

20:13.546 --> 20:15.214
Like, I'm ready to go!

20:15.214 --> 20:16.749
Let's go.
Let's go.

20:16.749 --> 20:19.652
So, Michael and Ryan,
the big ice cube in the room,

20:19.652 --> 20:24.590
is the $1.2 million for 5%,
imputes a $24 million valuation.

20:24.590 --> 20:26.292
You better be selling
a lot of them.

20:26.292 --> 20:27.793
We just
launched a year ago.

20:27.793 --> 20:29.395
We were building them
out of his garage.

20:29.395 --> 20:31.764
Literally 12 months ago,
we sold our first unit.

20:31.764 --> 20:33.666
To date, we've done
$4.9 million in sales.

20:33.666 --> 20:34.967
Wow.
Wow.

20:34.967 --> 20:36.235
Good for you.

20:36.235 --> 20:37.436
Over the 12 months,
$4.9 million,

20:37.436 --> 20:39.271
year to date,
$4.5 million.

20:39.271 --> 20:40.840
And we're on pace this month
to do $1.1 million.

20:40.840 --> 20:42.408
So walk us through
the economics.
Good job, guys.
Well done.

20:42.408 --> 20:43.776
What's your cost
to make them?

20:43.776 --> 20:45.544
Thank you, thank you.
What's it cost to make one?

20:45.544 --> 20:47.713
And how much do you sell it for,
and how do you sell it?

20:47.713 --> 20:49.281
Garrett: So we sell them
all on our website.

20:49.281 --> 20:52.051
And so this Plunge
is $4,800,

20:52.051 --> 20:53.486
so it's very affordable.
Wow.

20:53.486 --> 20:56.989
Our landed cost is $2,400,
and that does include shipping.

20:56.989 --> 20:58.591
Herjavec: Do you have
an installation service?

20:58.591 --> 20:59.759
That's the amazing
part of it.

20:59.759 --> 21:01.594
It shows up, they put it
wherever you want it.

21:01.594 --> 21:03.696
From there, you have about
15 minutes of setup.

21:03.696 --> 21:06.398
And that 15 minutes is mostly
filling it up with a hose.

21:06.398 --> 21:08.501
The question is how big
is your market, right?

21:08.501 --> 21:10.469
Totally.
Because what happens
when somebody comes up

21:10.469 --> 21:13.239
with a good product,
you get all the pent-up demand

21:13.239 --> 21:15.775
as people hear about it
and they dive in, right?
100%.

21:15.775 --> 21:17.810
So you get
this initial surge.

21:17.810 --> 21:22.214
But at a $24.5 million valuation
and only having 5%,

21:22.214 --> 21:26.519
you have to make $24 million
in distributable cash profits

21:26.519 --> 21:29.054
in order for us
to get our money back, right?

21:29.054 --> 21:31.957
I have to think in terms of not
only can I get my money back,

21:31.957 --> 21:33.926
but how much more money
can I make on it?

21:33.926 --> 21:35.694
And for you to come on here
with that valuation,

21:35.694 --> 21:36.829
I can't blame you.

21:36.829 --> 21:39.532
I can.
I'll do the blaming.

21:39.532 --> 21:42.535
Okay, so I like the deal
because of the revenue,

21:42.535 --> 21:44.436
but I also see lots
of competitors

21:44.436 --> 21:46.205
that could knock you off.

21:46.205 --> 21:47.640
I'll make you an offer.

21:47.640 --> 21:51.844
I'll give you the $1.2 million
for 18% equity,

21:51.844 --> 21:53.879
but I have to get
my money back somehow,

21:53.879 --> 21:57.516
so I get 18% of the
distributions, you get the rest.

21:57.516 --> 22:00.386
Every time you take
out a dollar, I get 18 cents.

22:01.253 --> 22:04.223
Greiner: Let me tell you what
I think. I agree with Mark.

22:04.223 --> 22:05.825
I think about, like,
how many years

22:05.825 --> 22:08.761
is it gonna take me
to get my money back?

22:08.761 --> 22:11.297
I wish you the best of luck,
but I'm out.

22:12.598 --> 22:15.201
So, guys,
is more money better?

22:15.201 --> 22:18.070
Like, is the $1.2 million,
when you've calculated,

22:18.070 --> 22:21.540
what you really need, or is it
like if you got more money,

22:21.540 --> 22:23.976
would it make life better,
would make things go faster?

22:23.976 --> 22:25.678
So $1.2 million
gets us --

22:25.678 --> 22:28.247
it's enough for 400 units
that we can build.

22:28.247 --> 22:29.448
Garrett: What we want
to do with the money

22:29.448 --> 22:30.850
is to really ramp up
production.

22:30.850 --> 22:32.885
Okay, I'm gonna
give you an offer.

22:32.885 --> 22:35.955
I'll give you the $1.2 million
for 20%.

22:35.955 --> 22:38.090
And it's gonna be in
the form of half a loan

22:38.090 --> 22:40.192
or line of credit,
whatever you prefer,

22:40.192 --> 22:41.660
because I think
that you really need.

22:41.660 --> 22:44.163
You just have
cash-flow problems.

22:44.163 --> 22:46.198
And then the other
50% up front.

22:46.198 --> 22:48.334
Got it. Thank you.

22:48.334 --> 22:50.336
I asked you a question about
cash because I wanted to see

22:50.336 --> 22:51.670
what you were doing with it.

22:51.670 --> 22:53.873
If you have more cash,
do things go faster?

22:53.873 --> 22:57.009
And it sounds like they do.

22:57.009 --> 23:00.079
I'll give you $2.4 million.

23:00.079 --> 23:03.015
$1.2 million
for straight equity.

23:03.015 --> 23:05.117
I want 15% for that.

23:05.117 --> 23:07.186
And I'll give you
the other $1.2 million

23:07.186 --> 23:08.787
as a straight-up loan.

23:08.787 --> 23:10.689
Same rate you would get
from the bank.

23:10.689 --> 23:14.093
Because I do think more money
will make things go faster.

23:14.093 --> 23:15.694
So that's my offer.

23:17.796 --> 23:19.765
Cuban: Guys, I'll simplify
all that, okay?

23:19.765 --> 23:24.236
I'll offer you
the $1.2 million, 15%, right?

23:24.236 --> 23:26.205
I'll finance
your purchase orders,

23:26.205 --> 23:28.908
and it's just got to be first
dollar back to me on the sale.

23:28.908 --> 23:32.411
And so if you finance 100 units
or 200, when you sell those,

23:32.411 --> 23:34.413
I get paid back first,
right?

23:34.413 --> 23:35.547
So it's just first dollar back.

23:35.547 --> 23:36.849
Got it.

23:36.849 --> 23:38.717
Greiner: So, you guys,
you now have four offers

23:38.717 --> 23:40.719
on the table.
What a lucky day for you guys.

23:40.719 --> 23:42.288
What are you
gonna do?

23:42.288 --> 23:45.291
Robert, would you
drop to 10%?

23:45.291 --> 23:48.327
I'd drop to 12%.

23:48.327 --> 23:50.329
Mark?
10%?

23:50.329 --> 23:58.604
