24:38.277 --> 24:40.245
Narrator: Next in the Tank
is an innovation

24:40.245 --> 24:42.214
to a common kitchen tool.

24:42.214 --> 24:47.386
♪♪

24:47.386 --> 24:52.491
♪♪

24:52.491 --> 24:55.260
Hi, Sharks. I'm Adam.
And I'm Josh.

24:55.260 --> 24:56.562
We're from Columbus,
Ohio,

24:56.562 --> 24:59.098
and we're the creators
of the Handy Pan.

24:59.098 --> 25:01.600
We're here seeking
a $10,000 investment

25:01.600 --> 25:03.235
for 20% equity
in our company.

25:03.235 --> 25:04.870
-[ Chuckles ]
-Gosh.

25:04.870 --> 25:06.839
Sharks, everybody loves
Taco Tuesday.

25:06.839 --> 25:08.340
You know
what nobody loves?

25:08.340 --> 25:10.442
Cleaning up the greasy,
disgusting mess

25:10.442 --> 25:12.311
that follows cooking
with a frying pan.

25:12.311 --> 25:13.579
We've all been there.

25:13.579 --> 25:15.814
You tried pinching the lid,
lose half your meat,

25:15.814 --> 25:18.117
still end up with grease
in your tacos.

25:18.117 --> 25:20.319
Or you do the spoon dance,
and you have to guess

25:20.319 --> 25:22.121
when your food
is done straining.

25:22.121 --> 25:25.157
Or you have the messy exchange
with a clunky colander

25:25.157 --> 25:27.593
that you still end up
having to clean in the end.

25:27.593 --> 25:29.028
That's where we come in.

25:29.028 --> 25:31.030
Introducing
the Handy Pan --

25:31.030 --> 25:33.565
a pan when you want it,
a strainer when you need it.

25:33.565 --> 25:35.901
With the simple push
of a button, boom!

25:35.901 --> 25:38.737
The amazing Handy Pan
becomes a strainer, too.

25:38.737 --> 25:40.639
-Ah.
-Bacon? No problem.

25:40.639 --> 25:43.008
Eating a little healthier?
Boom!

25:43.008 --> 25:45.177
Perfect for your veggies
and stir-fries.

25:45.177 --> 25:47.813
How about pasta night
with the family, Sharks?

25:47.813 --> 25:48.947
Boom!

25:48.947 --> 25:51.116
Now you cook your meat sauce
all in one pan.

25:51.116 --> 25:53.652
Cook your meat sauce
in one pan.

25:53.652 --> 25:54.920
Herjavec: Wow.
That's really clever.

25:54.920 --> 25:58.657
And the Handy Pot
is perfect for your pastas.

25:58.657 --> 25:59.958
What if you don't need
to strain?

25:59.958 --> 26:01.927
You're cooking something
that doesn't require it?

26:01.927 --> 26:04.430
No worries.
The patented design makes sure

26:04.430 --> 26:06.098
the strainer is always there
if you need it,

26:06.098 --> 26:08.000
but it's never in the way
if you don't need it.

26:08.000 --> 26:10.869
Conway: The Handy Pan is a
must-have for anyone who cooks.

26:10.869 --> 26:13.272
All right, Sharks,
let's get cooking.

26:13.272 --> 26:14.506
Without the grease,
of course.

26:14.506 --> 26:16.408
And you'll notice some samples
in front of you

26:16.408 --> 26:17.876
to try for yourselves
if you'd like.

26:17.876 --> 26:20.479
Josh, Adam, one of the hardest
things you can do

26:20.479 --> 26:21.647
is get on this show.

26:21.647 --> 26:23.582
Thousands of people apply.
Yes, sir.

26:23.582 --> 26:27.019
You did it,
and you're looking for...

26:27.019 --> 26:28.587
$10,000.
That is correct.

26:28.587 --> 26:29.755
[ Laughs ]

26:29.755 --> 26:31.190
-You're looking for --
-I think that's a first.

26:31.190 --> 26:32.891
That is a first.

26:32.891 --> 26:35.060
That's a great question.
I'm glad you asked.

26:35.060 --> 26:37.029
It took three years of effort
to get on this show.

26:37.029 --> 26:40.432
Basically, the valuation is that
we wanted to come in here

26:40.432 --> 26:42.968
with a number that doesn't
stand in the way of a deal.

26:42.968 --> 26:44.937
And have you sold any?

26:44.937 --> 26:47.406
So, currently, to date,
after a small production run,

26:47.406 --> 26:51.743
we've got $7,955.61
in sales.

26:51.743 --> 26:55.380
Really?
We understand
with $7,900 in sales,

26:55.380 --> 26:56.482
that we're not gonna
be able to ask

26:56.482 --> 26:58.250
for a million-dollar valuation,
of course.

26:58.250 --> 27:01.420
That doesn't stop anybody.
[ Laughter ]

27:01.420 --> 27:02.754
Corcoran: You've been
in business three years.

27:02.754 --> 27:04.690
Why so few sales?

27:04.690 --> 27:06.158
Great question.

27:06.158 --> 27:08.260
The sales have been
exclusively online.

27:08.260 --> 27:09.561
And what I believe is

27:09.561 --> 27:11.530
this is a product
that's ripe for retail.

27:11.530 --> 27:12.965
How much does it cost?

27:12.965 --> 27:14.900
$29.99,
and that included shipping.

27:14.900 --> 27:16.635
$29.99.
And what does it cost to make?

27:16.635 --> 27:19.505
It was $8.89 per unit.

27:19.505 --> 27:21.740
Landed,
we were at $11.43,

27:21.740 --> 27:24.343
but that was only based off
950 units.

27:24.343 --> 27:26.278
-Josh, what's --
-But it's highly demonstrable.

27:26.278 --> 27:28.447
Why do you think
your sales are so low?

27:28.447 --> 27:31.183
Personally, I think
that people like this,

27:31.183 --> 27:33.752
but it doesn't move the needle
enough in that mainstream market

27:33.752 --> 27:35.687
to make someone
a frying pan customer

27:35.687 --> 27:37.222
who's not already
a frying pan customer.

27:37.222 --> 27:40.359
But $7,000 -- there's got to be
a bigger reason.

27:40.359 --> 27:42.694
I feel like you're not
telling us something!

27:42.694 --> 27:43.996
Greiner:
Let's just ask honestly,

27:43.996 --> 27:45.797
what do you think
you did wrong?

27:45.797 --> 27:47.332
You know,
I think in hindsight,

27:47.332 --> 27:49.034
I think that we could have
promoted it better

27:49.034 --> 27:52.738
with our online videos,
advertising sales.

27:52.738 --> 27:55.574
That's not an arena that
either of us were in currently.

27:55.574 --> 27:57.009
So I think we had
some struggles there.

27:57.009 --> 27:58.844
What were you in?
What's your background?

27:58.844 --> 28:02.281
I started out
as a entry-level person

28:02.281 --> 28:04.283
in a office technologies
company.

28:04.283 --> 28:05.851
I ended up
as the director of service

28:05.851 --> 28:07.486
for 10 years
at that company.

28:07.486 --> 28:09.855
And then I've transferred
into real estate.

28:09.855 --> 28:11.957
Okay, and you?
I am an attorney,

28:11.957 --> 28:14.359
and I actually am a server
and a bartender

28:14.359 --> 28:16.061
a few nights a week
at a local restaurant.

28:16.061 --> 28:18.263
<i>And</i> an attorney?
What does that say
about your attorney skills?

28:18.263 --> 28:20.299
Yeah. Come on, man!

28:20.299 --> 28:21.900
It says I need a break
a few times a week

28:21.900 --> 28:23.368
and want to hit
the off switch.

28:23.368 --> 28:25.204
Good clients.

28:25.204 --> 28:26.605
That's where he finds
his clients, yeah.

28:26.605 --> 28:28.640
I love that job.
What area of law?

28:28.640 --> 28:30.175
Criminal defense,
mostly.

28:30.175 --> 28:31.343
Perfect!

28:31.343 --> 28:33.679
[ Laughter ]

28:33.679 --> 28:37.783
No, I'm gonna tell you why
it's 7,955 bucks

28:37.783 --> 28:38.884
or whatever it is.

28:38.884 --> 28:40.886
Nobody cares.
Chef Wonderful --

28:40.886 --> 28:42.821
It's not a product
that's ever going to sell.
Stop.

28:42.821 --> 28:44.256
-No! Are you kidding me?
-Stop!

28:44.256 --> 28:45.824
Well, then, how come
there's no sales, Mark?

28:45.824 --> 28:47.960
Well, let's ask
the right question then, right?

28:47.960 --> 28:49.962
How much money
have you spent on advertising?

28:51.029 --> 28:53.899
For that amount of sales,
we spent $553 on Facebook ads.

28:53.899 --> 28:56.268
There you go. Right?
It's a very, very hard

28:56.268 --> 28:59.705
to sell direct to consumer
online from your own website.

28:59.705 --> 29:01.240
So the next question becomes,

29:01.240 --> 29:03.075
did you try to sell these
on Amazon?

29:03.075 --> 29:04.810
We did not.

29:04.810 --> 29:07.079
Greiner: Oh, well,
there's the big miss.

29:07.079 --> 29:09.948
But, listen, I'm going to
completely disagree with Kevin.

29:09.948 --> 29:11.416
All right?

29:11.416 --> 29:14.386
So I think
that you probably

29:14.386 --> 29:17.256
just didn't have
the right marketing savvy.

29:17.256 --> 29:19.191
When you're cooking,
if you could just do this

29:19.191 --> 29:21.026
and drain out the grease --
eureka.

29:21.026 --> 29:22.961
And you don't have to
clean two things.
O'Leary: So, Lori...

29:22.961 --> 29:24.830
The great part about the design
and our patent

29:24.830 --> 29:27.399
is that it can fit
on any size pan.
Herjavec: You have a patent
for this?

29:27.399 --> 29:29.835
And you have a patent
that covers all of this?

29:29.835 --> 29:32.938
We have four patents.
We have design and utility
on what you're holding.

29:32.938 --> 29:37.209
We have design issued on pot
and pending utility on pot.

29:37.209 --> 29:38.877
So three of the four
are issued.

29:38.877 --> 29:42.547
The value of having
an attorney partner, right?

29:42.547 --> 29:44.449
So, listen,
we've got a great product.
Herjavec: Guys, I --

29:44.449 --> 29:46.285
Guys,
it's a great product.

29:46.285 --> 29:48.253
Here's what doesn't
make sense to me.

29:48.253 --> 29:51.390
You're obviously bright guys,
right?

29:51.390 --> 29:53.892
You're a lawyer.
Cuban:
But they got day jobs.

29:53.892 --> 29:55.661
Their back's not
against the wall.
No, no, I hear you.

29:55.661 --> 29:57.162
But we've had --
Over the 13 seasons,

29:57.162 --> 29:59.564
we've had people here
with three jobs,

29:59.564 --> 30:02.200
no experience,
never knew how to do video,

30:02.200 --> 30:04.069
never knew nothing
about social.

30:04.069 --> 30:06.305
But when they need it
and their back was

30:06.305 --> 30:09.141
up against the wall,
they made it happen.

30:09.141 --> 30:11.843
You haven't done <i>anything</i>
in three years.

30:11.843 --> 30:14.079
Because they got other jobs.
Their back is <i>not</i> against --

30:14.079 --> 30:15.080
-Is that an excuse?
-Wait, wait.

30:15.080 --> 30:16.248
Greiner:
You want to know something?

30:16.248 --> 30:17.249
I don't even care
about all this.

30:17.249 --> 30:19.618
You asked for $10,000
for 20%?

30:19.618 --> 30:21.953
I'll give it to you.
I have nothing to lose.

30:21.953 --> 30:23.455
-Done. We're done.
-Absolutely.

30:23.455 --> 30:24.456
-Done.
-We've got a deal.

30:24.456 --> 30:25.757
-Okay.
-There you go.

30:25.757 --> 30:27.626
-Smart, Lori. Smart.
-That's really true, though.

30:27.626 --> 30:29.261
I mean, seriously,
what do I have to lose?

30:29.261 --> 30:31.396
Absolutely.
Thank you so much.

30:31.396 --> 30:33.565
Okay.
[ Laughter ]

30:33.565 --> 30:35.167
Herjavec: Oh, my God.

30:35.167 --> 30:37.269
Yeah. Kaboom!

30:37.269 --> 30:39.237
Pleasure to meet all of you.
Thank you very much.

30:39.237 --> 30:40.739
Cuban: Congratulations, guys.
Good job.

30:40.739 --> 30:42.007
-Thanks.
-Check it out.

30:42.007 --> 30:44.076
Lori, why didn't you ask
for 50%?

30:44.076 --> 30:46.645
I don't want to be
a greedy savage like you.

30:46.645 --> 30:49.881
Conway: We came here.
Lori was exactly who we wanted.

30:49.881 --> 30:51.550
We thought
we had a good valuation

30:51.550 --> 30:53.318
to just make it
a no-brainer.

30:53.318 --> 30:56.588
We actually sat on the deck
of my house with my wife,

30:56.588 --> 30:59.791
drawing this on a napkin,
and she first said,

30:59.791 --> 31:02.527
"You guys are idiots.
I don't even know what that is."

31:02.527 --> 31:03.895
She probably
still thinks that.
And this guy said,

31:03.895 --> 31:05.163
"You won't be
calling us idiots

31:05.163 --> 31:06.231
when we have a deal
with Lori Greiner."

31:13.972 --> 31:16.308
